observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a.	advise the Municipal Accountant to (i) refrain from recording projects which are not covered by perfected contracts, not yet implemented/
delivered and/or unbilled; 


(ii) prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the overstatement of CIP-Infrastructure Assets and Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment accounts; 


(iii) record the donated vehicle and equipment in the books; and 


(iv) ensure only claims with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment;


b.	create an Inventory Committee who will spearhead the conduct of annual physical count of PPE and require the same to prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year; and

c.	require the Municipal Assessor or the designated LGU personnel to expedite the titling of recorded parcel of land in compliance with Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and Section 39 of P.D. No. 1445 to establish ownership thereof and to fully protect the interest of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

 a.	AOs to prepare the monthly RAAF and the Municipal Treasurer prepare the monthly CRAAF and submit the said monthly reports not later than the 5th day of the ensuing month to the Office of the Auditor;

b.	Revenue collectors particularly the RPT collectors to issue the pre-numbered official receipts in strict numerical sequence and refrain from using a new booklet until the previous one was fully issued and accounted;

c.	Municipal Treasurer to strictly monitor the receipts and issuances of AF, and ensure that all issued AF were duly accounted and corresponding collections were fully remitted.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

a.	LDRRM Officer to (i) strive for the timely and full implementation of the planned disaster-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objectives of the fund and the desired benefits; 



(ii) include in the MDRRMFIP the list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years under Special Trust Fund; 


(iii) coordinate with the donor for a copy of MOA and other documents that would serve as the basis of MAO for recording the donated equipment; 


(iv) furnish the Office of the Auditor with Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF within the reglementary period;


(v) submit a written explanation on the discrepancies noted in the distribution of sandbags; and 


(vi) provide the lacking documentations for procured items and submit proof of distribution for the rice, canned goods and other grocery items including hygiene kits; 

b.	Municipal Treasurer to prepare an inventory list of all items procured for DRRM and submit the same to the Audit Team; and

c.	Municipal Accountant to (i) record the donated equipment in the books; and 



(ii) perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims and ensure only those with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer including all Accountable Officers to (i) immediately transmit to the Audit Team the unsubmitted accounts and financial reports; 

(ii) strictly observe the timeframes on the submission of accounts and financial reports; and 


(iii) impose appropriate sanctions against those officials/employees concerned who have continuously disregarded the set deadline for the submission of the accounts/reports.

We recommended that Management:
a. direct the LDRRM Officer to (i) strive for the timely and full implementation of the planned disaster-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objectives of the fund and the desired benefits; (ii) include in the MDRRMFIP the list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years under Special Trust Fund; and (iii) furnish the Office of the Auditor with Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF within the reglementary period;
b. facilitate the hiring of additional staff for LDRRM Office to comply with the required three (3) technical staff responsible for administration and training; research and planning; and operations and warning;
c. advise the BAC to ensure that the proper mode of procurement was resorted/adopted for every procurement transaction; and
d. instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) submit the aforementioned vouchers and supporting documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor; (ii) perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims and ensure only those with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment.

We recommended that Management:
a. intensify the information campaign on “No Segregation, No Collection Policy” and encourage the active participation of constituents, particularly the market vendors and education commercial/business establishments in the proper waste disposal from source;
b. prioritize the rehabilitation/construction of the Municipal MRF building to ensure compliance with Section 33 of R.A. No. 9003;
c. expedite the purchase of vehicle specifically designed for the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes by providing an adequate budget thereon; and
d. undertake proper information dissemination like the conduct of seminars and production of posters/tarpaulins on the harmful effects to public health of the smoke from burned solid wastes.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the:

Municipal Accountant to (i) maintain SLCs for each commodity/stock; 




(ii) record all procurement of inventory supplies in the books of accounts using the Perpetual Inventory System; 




(iii) draw the necessary journal entries to recognize the expenditures based on the SSMI; and 




(iv) be more vigilant to ensure that issued supplies and materials were recorded to appropriate expense accounts; and



Municipal Treasurer to (i) maintain stock cards for each item of inventory; 




(ii) regularly reconcile the stock cards with the SLCs of the Accounting Office; 




(iii) report the issuances of supplies thru the SSMI which shall be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording to appropriate Expenses accounts; and

(iv) conduct physical count of stocks of all supplies and materials and submit relative reports to the Office of the Auditor and other offices concerned on a semi-annual basis.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant analyze and draw the appropriate journal entries to (a) reclassify the completed projects in the CIP accounts to appropriate asset accounts; 


(b) reclassify, liquidate and transfer the completed PPE in the TF to GF; 


(c) locate pertinent records and closely monitor the CIP account thru the maintenance of subsidiary records and other accounting record; 



(d) provide depreciation expense amounting to ₱3,054,588.56 to various depreciable assets mentioned above; and 

(e) reclassify the improperly recorded PPEs for accurate and fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the LCE:

a.	direct the LDRRM Officer to (i) strive for the timely and full implementation of LDRRM-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits; (ii) include in the LDRRMFIP the list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; and (iii) furnish the Office of the Auditor with Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in the required format through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; 

b.	consider the hiring of additional staff for LDRRM Office to comply with the required three (3) technical staff responsible for administration and training; research and planning; and operations and warning;

c.	instruct the Municipal Accountant and BAC to (i) submit the aforementioned required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for proper/further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Sections 4(5) and 4(6) of PD No. 1445; (ii) perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to ensure that these are properly supported with complete documentation and proper approval by authorized officials/representatives; and (iii) comply with the required posting requirements of GPPB Circular 2020-001 for information purposes; and

d.	require the Property Officer to diligently prepare/maintain inventory records such as SCs and PCs, Monthly RSMI, RIS and Inventory List of all procured and donated items and coordinate with the Accounting Office for the periodic reconciliation of both inventory records.

We appreciated the effort of Management in the prompt remittance of the current contributions and loan amortizations due the GSIS and for complying strictly with the provisions of RA No. 8291. Notwithstanding, we recommended that the Accounting Office (a) ensure that all contributions and loans withheld during the period will be remitted in full; 


(b) exert more effort in the analysis of the outstanding balance of ₱523,117.75 and cause the remittance thereof once the correct amount and details are duly established; and 

(c) draw adjusting entry to adjust the Due to GSIS account.

We recognized the Management’s good practice of promptly remitting premiums, loan amortizations, and other contributions to the HDMF. However, we recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Accountant to: (a) draw the necessary adjusting entry to adjust the Due to Pag-IBIG account for the PhilHealth remittance amounting to ₱48,462.18 erroneously posted to the account;

(b) instruct the concerned personnel to determine the exact amount to be remitted to fully comply with the provisions of RA No. 9679; and 

(c) investigate/trace the details of the unremitted balances from prior periods and immediately remit the same or effect necessary adjustments, if warranted.

