direct the LDRRM Officer to (i) strive for the timely and full implementation of LDRRM-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits; (ii) include in the LDRRMFIP the list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; and (iii) furnish the Office of the Auditor with Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in the required format through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;
consider the hiring of additional staff for LDRRM Office to comply with the required three (3) technical staff responsible for administration and training; research and planning; and operations and warning;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and BAC to (i) submit the aforementioned required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for proper/further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Sections 4(5) and 4(6) of PD No. 1445; (ii) perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to ensure that these are properly supported with complete documentation and proper approval by authorized officials/representatives; and (iii) comply with the required posting requirements of GPPB Circular 2020-001 for information purposes; and
require the Property Officer to diligently prepare/maintain inventory records such as SCs and PCs, Monthly RSMI, RIS and Inventory List of all procured and donated items and coordinate with the Accounting Office for the periodic reconciliation of both inventory records.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive: 

a.	instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to ensure the completeness of all information and supporting documents submitted by the bidders during the evaluation of technical documents and eligibility check;

b. 	advise the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the noted documentary deficiencies and make sure that only disbursement vouchers with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment;


c. 	instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), the Municipal Engineer and officials/end-users concerned to properly plan the PPAs to be included in the 20% Local Development Plan and refrain from charging expenditures which do not partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures or those not relevant to the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes as identified under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1; 

d. 	require the MPDC and the Municipal Engineer to monitor regularly the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time; and


e.	expedite the finalization and approval of the rental rates and terms and conditions on the use of the solar dryers to immediately serve its intended purpose.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:

a. 	MDRRMC to (i) monitor and evaluate the utilization of MDRRMF based on the programs, projects and activities listed in the MDRRMFIP; 

(ii)   ensure compliance with the prescribed minimum standards for disaster preparedness developed by the DILG and LGA; 


(iii) include in the MDRRMFIP the list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended MDRRMF of previous years; and (iv)    furnish the Office of the Auditor with Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in the required format through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; and

b. 	Municipal Accountant to perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to ensure that these are properly supported with complete documentation and proper approval by authorized officials/ representatives.

We recommended that management:

a.  	formalize the creation of a new MESWMB and institutionalize its roles and functions thru the issuance of the corresponding Executive Order duly signed by the incumbent Municipal Mayor;


b.  	prioritize the rehabilitation/construction of the Municipal MRF building to ensure compliance with Section 33 of R.A. No. 9003;

c.  	expedite the purchase of vehicle specifically designed for the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes by providing adequate budget thereon; and


d.  	intensify the information and education campaign to stop totally the open burning of solid wastes in the different barangays and solicit the assistance of the Sanggunian in the promulgation of a local ordinance prohibiting such wrong practice among the community members and set fines and penalties for violators.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to: 

a. 	ensure that all expired contracts in the Public Market have been renewed immediately and implement strictly the terms and conditions stated thereto;


b. 	maintain a registry book containing the vital information about the stallholders and ensure that it is regularly updated; and

c. 	exert more effort to (i) intensify revenue collection strategies such as periodic sending of notices/demand letters to all delinquent stallholders;



(ii) enforce the automatic cancellation of the contracts of lease of stallholders who failed to pay for three consecutive months; and


(iii) avail of all legal and administrative remedies allowed under R.A. No. 7160.

We recommended and management agreed to (a) continue to adopt the good practice of promptly remitting premiums, loan amortizations, and other contributions to the Home Development Mutual Fund;


(b) instruct the concerned personnel to determine the exact amount to be remitted to fully comply with the provisions of Republic Act (R.A.) No. 9679; and 


(c) investigate/trace the details of the unremitted balances from prior periods and immediately remit the same or effect necessary adjustments, if warranted.

We recommended and management agreed to:

(a)	plan carefully and align properly the charges against the 5% LDRRMF and ensure that only those PPAs consistent with the purposes of the Fund are included in the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Plan (LDRRMP);



(b)	consider the relocation of the CCTV cameras to the geographically determined disaster-prone areas such as seashores, riverbanks, low land areas and the like;



(c)	refrain from utilizing PPEs purchased out of the 5% LDRRMF to non – disaster related PPAs; and



(d)	require the BAC to submit all the documents listed above, otherwise, we will issue the corresponding Notice of Suspension (NS) or Notice of Disallowance (ND).

