We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to 

reconcile their records monthly;




be directly involved in the preparation of the SCBAA and other financial reports;

divide the workload properly among staffs, and continually orient them on their specific assignments to prevent incurrence of the same deficiencies;
inculcate in the minds of the heads of the Accounting and Budget Offices that the outputs of their Offices are reflections of their commitment and zeal as public servants; and

find a way to augment the existing permanent personnel in the Accounting Office to ensure timely and accurate reporting system.

We recommended and management agreed to: 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant, and not the Municipal Budget Officer, to submit all CAVs, TLs and SDs to the ATL within seven (7) days after release of check in case of cash advances covering the Confidential Fund;
Limit the granting of cash advances to activities/expenditures specifically authorized under COA Circular No. 97 – 002 dated February 10, 1997; and authorize the granting of cash advance to elected municipal officials to the extent of their traveling expenses and similar claims only;


Discontinue the practice of purchasing goods out of cash advance; otherwise, the same shall be disallowed in audit; and
Issue demand letters to the concerned municipal officials/ employees for their unliquidated cash advances as at December 31, 2016; otherwise, institute appropriate administrative and legal actions against accountable officers who continually disregard the notices/ letters sent to them.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that management require the:
Inventory Committee to submit the completed RPCPPE and henceforth prepare and submit yearly to the Auditor a duly certified and approved RPCPPE for all types of PPE not later than January 31 of each year and IIRUP immediately after inspection of the unserviceable property;
MTO maintain Property Card;
analyze and reconcile the property records and accounting records using the latest available RPCPPE and IIRUP; and
Accountant to make the necessary adjustments/correc-tions in the books and henceforth review the entries made by the Accounting staff to reflect the correct balances of the PPE.

We recommended and the management agreed to:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, and not the Municipal Budget Officer, to submit all CAVs, TLs and SDs to the ATL within seven (7) days after release of check in case of cash advances covering the Confidential Fund;
Limit the granting of cash advances to activities/expenditures specifically authorized under COA Circular No. 97 – 002 dated February 10, 1997; and authorize the granting of cash advance to elected municipal officials to the extent of their traveling expenses and similar claims only;
Discontinue the practice of purchasing goods out of cash advance; otherwise, the same shall be disallowed in audit; and
Issue demand letters to the concerned municipal officials/ employees for their unliquidated cash advances as at December 31, 2016; otherwise, institute appropriate administrative and legal actions against accountable officers who continually disregard the notices/ letters sent to them.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:
determine the details of the unutilized PDAF Funds and Other Trust Fund Balances;



see to it that all balances of PDAF trust funds which are not covered by Notice of Cash Allocations but only by Special Allotment Release Orders, whether obligated or not, and the Other Trust Account balances be reverted to the Unappropriated Surplus of the General Fund;
perform reconciliation work with source agencies to ascertain the nature of the transferred funds, i.e., if the funds received require liquidation or are to be treated simply as subsidy to the LGU;
if due for liquidation, prepare and submit liquidation reports for the expended portion and cause the return to the source agencies all unutilized balances of the fund transfers; and



improve the safekeeping of important documents especially MOAs and TAs for future references.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct:
the Local Development Council, the Sanggunian and the Municipal Budget Officer to refrain from appropriating/alloca-ting funds for programs/projects/activities (PPAs) under the 20% Development Fund which are not capital in nature and    ensure that the Fund is only utilized for its intended purpose;



refrain from proposing non-capital investment projects under the Fund;



the Local Development Council abide strictly with the guidelines on the planning and implementation of the projects/activities funded under the 20% Development Fund;  and


the Municipal Budget Officer  carefully determine the unexpended balance of the appropriations pertaining to the unimplemented projects/activities which should be  appropriately placed under Continuing Appropriation to fund the unimplemented/still on-going infrastructure projects for completion in the ensuing year.

We recommended that management:

establish a GFPS and Local GAD Code to ensure that resources are allocated and utilized for the formulation and operationalization of the GAD Code in accordance with the Magna Carta of  Women (MCW) and form an Executive Committee, a Technical Working Group  and/or Secretariat to hasten gender mainstreaming;

ensure the establishment of a VAW Desk in every barangay within their jurisdiction, and provide technical and financial assistance for its operations ;

direct the Municipal Budget Officer to submit the annual GPB to the PPDO of the Provincial Government to ensure the alignment of the municipal/city PPAs with the priorities of the province and to the DlLG Regional Offices for its review and approval;

align the PPAs charged to GAD with COA Circular No. 2014-001 and PPAs identified or authorized in specific laws for gender and development and require the submission of its required reports for the approval of PCW; and


stop appropriating PPAs which are not GAD related and ensure that PPAs to be included in the budget addresses gender issues and concerns and are geared towards the achievement of the purpose of promoting gender-responsive governance, protecting and fulfilling women's human rights and promoting women's economic empowerment pursuant to the above-named regulations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive together with the LDRRMC to:
align the LDRRMP  with the NDRRMP for 2011-2028;
ensure that the required composition of the Council be strictly adhered to in   carrying    out its powers and functions in disaster related activities;
direct the Accounting Unit to prepare a Journal Entry Voucher to take up recording of inventories, construction in progress, and equipment to its proper account, including the recognition of depreciation charges thereon, to maintain separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for LDRRMF and see to it that the goods for distribution were supported with a list that goods were duly receipted; and
direct the Budget and Accounting Units to determine the amount of MOOE balance at year-end and transfer to Trust Fund books using the new chart of accounts.

Furthermore, transfer the funds for the erroneous payment of construction of LDRRM Office from General Fund to Trust Fund amounting to ₱907,129.00.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
install a much stricter internal control over the municipality’s cash management system in order to safeguard and protect the coffers and interest of the LGU;



require the job order personnel to apply for fidelity bond since they are in the custody of public funds;



restrict access of unauthorized persons by using the windows intended for the collection activities and advice vendors to sell their products outside the LGU;




consider the separation of the Municipal Treasurer’s Office from other offices;




require the collecting officers to prepare Requisition and Issue Slip and Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms for the receipt and issuance of accountable forms to them to support the Consolidated RAAF. Likewise, appoint a custodian of accountable forms in order to establish and tighten control in the issuance of all accountable forms; 

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to supervise the concerned officers and employees to ensure that all collections are remitted intact and daily to the Liquidating Officer. Verify both used and unused accountable forms to ascertain that all collections are actually remitted by the collectors; and

advice the Assistant Municipal Treasurer to monitor and check the liquidation of collections of collectors and ensure that no issuance of Accountable Forms be made unless previous stub requisitioned are liquidated/submitted to the Liquidating Officer.
